on—but watching an addict relapse or an inmate’s execution are much more devastating setbacks. Summers Effler finds that overcoming these obstacles, recovering from failure, and maintaining the integrity of the group require a constant process of emotional fine-tuning, and she demonstrates how activists do this through thoughtful analysis and a lucid rendering of their deeply affecting stories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAltruism. 0aEmotions. 0aSocial groups. 0aSocial movementsvCase studies. 0aSocial movementsxCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aemotion, feeling, rhythm, social studies, movement, sociology, academic, scholarly, research, failure, defeat, activism, activist, risk, physical, financial, wellness, safety, finance, money, turnover, burnout, ethography, ethnographic, fieldwork, death penalty, anti, stop, catholic, poverty, community, communal, member, altruism, history, historical.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226188676423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226188676/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles